[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'The Google Apps team has been on fire lately, and this week they just dropped a massive upgrade to Opal. Now, if you do not know what Opal is, it is Google\'s no-code mini app builder. By the way, you can also access it directly inside the Gemini app via gems. Let\'s say you'

[00:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'want to build an app that creates a visual storybook or one that summarizes the news into an infographic with audio and video, all from one single prompt. Opal connects the right models within'

[00:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the Google ecosystem and builds that app for you. No code required, not a single line. Now, the way Opal used to work has completely changed. They introduced four big things.'

[00:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Number one, and this is the biggest one, is agent step. Instead of you picking which models to use at every step, the agent now analyzes your goals in real time and figures out the best tools on'

[00:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'its own. Number two is memory. Your Opals can now remember things across sessions, your name, your preferences, your brand style. The more you use it, the smarter it gets. Number three is'

[01:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'dynamic routing. The agent can now choose different paths based on logic you define, like routing a new client one way and an existing client another way. And number four is interactive'

[01:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'chat. The agent can now pause and actually ask you questions mid-workflow if it needs some information before moving on. So, in this video, I\'m going to double-click on each one of those so you\'re crystal clear on what they are'

[01:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and how you can take advantage of this massive update. Before that, a quick disclaimer, all opinions are my own [music] and do not belong to my employer. All right, let\'s get into it. All right, so if you\'ve never used Opal, you need to come to labs.google.com, and'

[01:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this is where you will find Opal. And then here you can sign in with your own Google ID. So, once you sign in, you will land into the Opal platform, and here you can go ahead and create new. Now, there are two options for you to'

[01:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'create the Opal. You can describe what you want, and it will build it out for you, or you can do it step-by-step, which is more manual in nature. So, you can start with the user input and then add some more details. But, what we\'re'

[02:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'going to do is we\'re going to start with giving it a prompt, which is "Build me a client meeting prep app that asks about the client and meeting purposes, routes differently for new versus existing'

[02:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'clients, researches the company profile, remembers my preferences and outputs a beautiful interactive HTML briefing page with company overview, key people talking points, recent news, and a short video summary." So, this is a pretty'

[02:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'sophisticated prompt that I\'ve given. I\'m asking it to do a lot of different things. Now, the idea here is to show you how Opal is able to connect to all of the different Google models in order to'

[02:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'create an end-to-end app like this within a very short amount of time. So, in this one, I have asked it to ask my preferences about the company and then go research about the specific company'

[02:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and then come back to me with a video summary of it. And before I could even finish talking, it is able to create the app for us. Now, here this becomes the user inputs, as you can see. So, it is going to ask for'

[03:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'three different user inputs. And then when I click on this is where you will see that this is the brand new agent mode for us, right? So, earlier what used to happen is instead of having the agent decide, um this will actually'

[03:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'create multiple blocks, and each block will do its own jobs. In this case, you know what the new update has allowed it to do is it will give the agent the objective, it will give the agent some'

[03:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'of the tools, and then the agent is going to do that job for us. And then here again, we have given the agent the job to create the video summary. And lastly, we are creating an HTML output, right? As as we have asked. So, what'

[03:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'we\'re going to do is we\'re going to run this, and we can go to the app and start running with it. So, let\'s say that the name of the company that I want to meet is Google. And let\'s say that it is an existing Let\'s say it\'s a new client.'

[03:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And the purpose of the meeting is to help Google with marketing solutions. So, that\'s the purpose of the meeting that I\'m describing. As it starts to work, you can actually come back and see these arrows showing the flow. And at'

[04:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'any point in time, you can actually go to the console and see exactly which step it is, right? So, here it is in this particular step right now, and you can see the other steps where it has'

[04:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'already caught the data. And each one of the these steps are going to get get populated, right? So, here it\'s already in the agent session and has generated the meeting brief. So, this is what the output of the agent'

[04:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'already looks like. It has the purpose of the meeting, company overview, and stuff like that. And then now the agent session is already on, so you can see everything um very clearly shown here, which is the particular model which it is calling. It is all already'

[04:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'initializing the video summary. It\'s also adding music. It is starting to define the scene planning, etc. So, you can see the agent mode really working on our behalf over here. Earlier, under the hood what it would do is it would create'

[05:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'multiple different nodes for the same purpose. It will still do the job, but in this case now you\'re seeing a very simple, less complicated structure, and Google really leveraging or Opal really'

[05:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'leveraging the power of agentic frameworks here, right? So, that is what you\'re going to see in a very short amount of time. While it is doing that, what I also want to show you is what are the different tools that the agent is able to use. For example, if I press'

[05:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this at the rate button, you\'re able to see all of these interesting tools that is possible. So, you can see you can use memory, you can use notebook LM, and another new tool which they have created, which is go to. That means if and else for that matter, right? If'

[05:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this, then go to that particular node. If not, then go to this particular node. And then they also have search maps, they have search web, and get weather. Search web is where you\'re using Google search. Search maps is where you\'re using Google Maps. And then get weather'

[05:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'is a weather API, right? So, all of these things are directly built in as tools for the agent to actually leverage whenever it is generating the output for us. So, if you look at this, these are the new updates. You\'re actually seeing'

[06:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'them in action here. You\'re seeing the agent taking an action. You\'re seeing all of these different tools. For example, this is the memory tool, which is brand new, so it keeps this in memory whenever we are working in the next one.'

[06:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So, this will always be in the context. And then you also saw some other tools as well. Okay? So, looks like it has created what we have asked for. So, let\'s look at the output over here. And this is the output. This is the'

[06:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'company overview. It\'s in a beautiful HTML format. This is the leadership, etc. So, let me just play this and see what it has generated. All right. So, it has used the standard'

[06:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '8-second model in order to create this, but you can already see that it has found the key stakeholders, who\'s the CEO, etc. Who is It has found the key stakeholders and the leadership, and it'

[07:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'has also found the last 6 months of recent news, right? So, you can obviously use something like this, and you may not have to use the video generation all the time. If you\'re going for a meeting, this would be a great way for you to get prepared for the meeting.'

[07:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'You can actually create this Opal, and then every time, based on the topic that you\'re asking, it is going to research for you. So, this is a fantastic example of the upgraded Opal for you. So, that\'s the massive Opal upgrade in action.'

[07:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Agent step, memory, dynamic routing, interactive chat. And you just saw all of them working together in one app that I built with a single prompt. What really impressed me was how much simpler'

[07:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the workflow has become. Earlier, Opal would wire up 10 to 15 different nodes. Now, the agent handles it for Opal. Where I think it\'s still early is the output quality. The video generation'

[07:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'used the standard 8-second model. Now, I would love to see longer-form video options. And also, the HTML output was good, but not yet at the level where I would present it directly to a client without some clean up. So, overall, the'

[08:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'direction is clear. Google is turning Opal from a simple workflow builder into a proper agentic platform. And the fact that you can build something like this with one prompt and absolutely no code, that\'s pretty fantastic. So, that was'

